                                                                                                               Industry heaves a sigh of relief 
          OUR CORRESPONDENT                              
	New Delhi, April 13: Industry leaders today said the successful end to the Satyam bidding process showed the countrys ability to handle complex corporate issues.        
	The smooth completion of the bidding for Satyam demonstrates that India has adequate legal and institutional mechanism for handling and resolving a major corporate crisis, said Harshpati Singhania, president of the Federation of Indian Chambers of Commerce and Industry.         
	He said the deft handling of the issue would send a very positive signal to the global community and rebuild Indian firms credibility among their peers.        
	Software services association Nasscom said the acquisition of Satyam would give Tech Mahindra a broader foothold in terms of service offerings and vast geography.        
	Infosys also commended Tech Mahindras bid for Satyam. It is commendable that the board at Satyam has been able to bring to an end the uncertainty surrounding Satyams future, Infosys CEO S. Gopalakrishnan said. The government has addressed the issue quickly and responsibly, he said, adding, Overall it is a good thing that the issue is put behind us.        
	According to Chandrajit Banerjee, director-general of the CII, Tech Mahindra is a competent IT services provider. It will help Satyam to regain its status.         
	Assocham president Sajjan Jindal said, Its a good news for the entire market. The development will help stabilise Satyams market value, benefitting its clients and employees, Jindal said.                                                                                                                                        
